<h2>Full Wrap vs. Partial Wrap</h2>
<p>A <strong>full wrap</strong> covers 100% of the vehicle and delivers maximum brand impact. A <strong>partial wrap</strong> covers 40–70% of the vehicle — focusing on the areas most visible in traffic, at job sites, and in parking lots. Studies show partial wraps deliver <strong>70–80% of the visual impact</strong> of a full wrap at significantly less cost.</p>
<p>Partial wraps are ideal for:</p>
<figure class="supp-image-block"><img alt="Partial vehicle wrap Chicago" height="420" loading="lazy" src="/images/exalt_air_pick_up_truck.webp" width="1200"/><figcaption>Partial vehicle wrap Chicago — Chicago Fleet Wraps · (312) 597-1286</figcaption></figure>
<ul>
<li>Small businesses entering fleet branding for the first time</li>
<li>Companies testing vehicle advertising before committing to full wraps</li>
<li>Vehicles that are only partially visible (parked against walls, in driveways)</li>
<li>Budget-conscious fleet rollouts that can be expanded later</li>
<li>Vehicles with complex body lines where full wraps aren't cost-effective</li>
</ul>
<p>Read our detailed comparison: <a href="/post/full-wrap-vs-partial-wrap/" style="color:var(--gold)">Full Wrap vs. Partial Wrap →</a></p>
<h2>Same Premium Materials</h2>
<p>Every partial wrap uses the same premium cast vinyl as our full wraps — <strong>Avery Dennison MPI 1105</strong> or <strong>3M IJ180-CV3</strong> — rated for 5–7 years of outdoor durability. No shortcuts, no calendered vinyl, no compromise on quality. See our <a href="/materials/" style="color:var(--gold)">Materials Guide →</a></p>
